explanation:
● The Non-Cooperation Movement (NCM) (1920-22) was a major Indian movement led by Mahatma Gandhi against British rule. Rowlatt Act of 1919, the imposition of martial law in Punjab, the Jallainwala Bagh massacre, discontent with the Government of India Act, 1919 and the Khilafat issue were major reasons behind the launch of the movement. Swaraj was the major goal of the Non-cooperation Movement. So, statement 1 is correct.
● The Indian National Congress approved a non-cooperation programme at a special session in Calcutta (September 1920) until the wrongs of the Punjab and Khilafat were righted and swaraj was established. Lala Lajpat Rai was the President of this special session. So, statement 2 is not correct.
● The NCM, in the beginning, was to include:
○ boycott of government schools and colleges;
○ boycott of law courts and dispensation of justice through panchayats instead. So, statement 3 is correct.
○ boycott of legislative councils;
○ boycott of foreign cloth and use of khadi instead;
○ renunciation of government honours and titles.
So, only two of the above statements are correct.
Therefore, option (b) is the correct answer.
